+For the model in Section~\ref{sec:model}, we evaluated
+Eq.~\ref{eq:first-crossing-integral} on the complete grid
+\begin{equation}
+\mathcal A_{\mathrm{explore}}
+=\{0.001,0.002,\ldots,0.200\}.
+\label{eq:exploratory-alpha-grid}
+\end{equation}
+The calculation uses log-domain Gaussian tail probabilities. At a crossing,
+$\alpha\sum_{g=0}^2w_gq(c_*;|M_g(z)|,s_g)=1$, and hence
+$0\leq\ell_\alpha(z)\leq1$. Truncating the factor integral to $[-8,8]$
+therefore omits at most $2\Phi(-8)<1.25\times10^{-15}$. For every level in
+Eq.~\ref{eq:exploratory-alpha-grid}, the first-crossing branch has one switch
+between two roots as a function of $z$. The code locates the corresponding
+tangency, splits the factor integral there, and applies adaptive
+Gauss--Kronrod quadrature to the two smooth pieces. The largest reported
+quadrature error estimate over the 200 runs is $2.24\times10^{-10}$.
+
+The complete code and 200-row output are supplied as
+\texttt{evaluate\_s4\_first\_crossing.py} and
+\texttt{s4\_first\_crossing\_grid.csv}. Selected values are
